/***************************************************************
 * File:    utilities/lists.doc
 * Purpose: Description of facilities for linked lists.
 * Author:  Karl Abrahamson
 ***************************************************************/

 Lists of various types are provided, with a few basic operations.  
 To add a new list kind, modify type list_union, add a new 
 discriminator, make a new cons function, and modify function 
 set_head in lists.c.

 ****************************************************************
 *			FUNCTIONS				*
 ****************************************************************

cons functions
--------------

general_cons(h,t,k)	returns cons(h,t), where h has kind k. */

str_cons(h,t)		This and the other cons functions perform 
expr_cons(h,t)		specialized conses.
type_cons(h,t)
ctc_cons(h,t)
gic_cons(h,t)
int_cons(h,t)
file_cons(h,t)


General functions
-----------------

append(a,b)		returns the concatenation of lists a and b.

reverse_list(l)		returns the reversal of l.

str_member(s,l)		is n if s occurs in l at position n, where the first
			member of l is at position 1.  Returns 0 if s does
			not occur in l.
			!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!
			Equality tests are done by ==, so strings must be
			in the string table
			!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!

int_member(n,l)		is true just when integer n is a member of list l.

pop(s)			pops list s, as a stack.

subscript(l,n)		Returns the n^th tail of l.  If n = 1, returns l, else
			returns subscript(tail(l), n-1).  Returns nil
			if l has fewer than n members.

Reference count management for members
--------------------------------------

bump_head(k,h)	  	does a bump on h, where h has type HEAD_TYPE
 			and k tells its kind.
 
drop_head(k,h)	  	does a drop on h, where h has type HEAD_TYPE
 			and k tells its kind.
 
set_head(l,k,h)	  	sets the kind of list cell l to k, and the head
 			to h.
 

Storage management
------------------

allocate_list()		returns a pointer to a new list cell.

set_list(x,l)		Set variable x to l.  x is double indirect.  To
			achieve the effect of an assignment x = l, do
			SET_LIST(x,l).

bump_list(l)		Increment the reference count of list l.

drop_list(l)		Decrement the reference count of list l, and
			free l if the reference count goes to 0.
